.TH LIVE-SERVER 1 "2026-07-11" "live-server 2.7.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
live-server \- lightweight static file server with live reload
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B live-server
[\fB\-L\fR|\fB\-\-log-level\fR]
[\fB\-R\fR|\fB\-\-print-request\fR]
[\fB\-U\fR|\fB\-\-live-reload\fR]
[\fB\-W\fR|\fB\-\-live-hard-reload\fR]
[\fB\-H\fR|\fB\-\-host\fR]
[\fB\-K\fR|\fB\-\-keep-alive\fR]
[\fB\-M\fR|\fB\-\-max-conns\fR]
[\fB\-T\fR|\fB\-\-threads\fR]
[\fB\-F\fR|\fB\-\-log-file\fR]
[\fB\-p\fR|\fB\-\-pass\fR]
[\fB\-u\fR|\fB\-\-user\fR]
[\fB\-B\fR|\fB\-\-browser\fR]
[\fB\-i\fR|\fB\-\-ignore\fR]
[\fB\-I\fR|\fB\-\-dir\fR]
[\fB\-O\fR|\fB\-\-poll\fR]
[\fB\-?\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR]
[\fB\-\-usage\fR]
[\fB\-V\fR|\fB\-\-version\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B live-server
is a zero-dependency, single-binary static file server written in C17 for local
development. It serves files over HTTP/1.1 with correct MIME types, ETag/conditional
requests, byte-range support, and keep-alive. Optional live reload injects a
Server-Sent Events client into HTML responses and broadcasts reload events when
the filesystem changes.

The server uses a fixed-size thread pool with a circular work queue — no
thread-per-connection, no async runtime, no external libraries beyond POSIX
and pthreads. On Linux it uses \fBsendfile()\fR for zero-copy static file transfer;
on macOS it uses native \fBkqueue\fR for event-driven file watching.

All configuration is via command-line flags; there are no config files,
environment variables, or hidden state.
.SH OPTIONS
.\" Server identity
.SS "Server Identity"
.TP
\fB\-I\fR, \fB\-\-dir\fR \fI<DIR>\fR
\fI<DIR>\fR to serve. Defaults to current working directory. Must exist and be
readable. Symlinks are followed; the resolved path is cached at startup.
.TP
\fB\-P\fR, \fB\-\-port\fR \fI<PORT>\fR
TCP port to listen on \fI<PORT>\fR. Default: \fB8080\fR.
.TP
\fB\-H\fR, \fB\-\-host\fR \fI<HOST>\fR
Bind address \fI<HOST>\fR. Default: \fBlocalhost\fR (loopback only). Use \fB0.0.0.0\fR to
accept connections from other machines on the LAN (e.g. mobile testing).
.TP
\fB\-B\fR, \fB\-\-browser\fR \fI<CMD>\fR
Launch a browser on startup. The argument is passed to \fBexeclp(3)\fR;
common values: \fBopen\fR (macOS), \fBxdg-open\fR (Linux), \fBfirefox\fR,
\fBchrome\fR. If the command fails, a warning is logged and the server continues.

.\" Concurrency
.SS "Concurrency"
.TP
\fB\-T\fR, \fB\-\-threads\fR \fI<NUM>\fR
Thread pool size \fI<NUM>\fR. Default: \fB2\fR. Each worker pulls tasks from a
shared circular queue (4096 slots) protected by a mutex and two condition
variables. The accept loop blocks when the queue is full, providing natural
backpressure.
.TP
\fB\-K\fR, \fB\-\-keep-alive\fR \fI<SECS>\fR
Keep-alive timeout in seconds \fI<SECS>\fR. Default: \fB3\fR. A value of 0
disables keep-alive entirely (each request gets a fresh connection). When
enabled, the server sets \fBSO_RCVTIMEO\fR on the socket and reuses the
connection for subsequent requests from the same client.

.\" Rate limiting
.SS "Rate Limiting"
.TP
\fB\-M\fR, \fB\-\-max-conns\fR \fI<NUM>\fR
Maximum concurrent connections per client IP. Default: \fB0\fR
(unlimited). Implemented as a dynamic open-addressing hash table (djb2 hash,
linear probing) that doubles in size at 75% load factor. IP strings are owned
by the table and freed when the count drops to zero.

.\" Authentication
.SS "Authentication"
.TP
\fB\-u\fR, \fB\-\-user\fR \fI<USER>\fR
Enable HTTP Basic Authentication with the given username. Requires \fB\-\-pass\fR.
Default: \fBadmin\fR if only \fB\-\-pass\fR is given.
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-pass\fR \fI<PASS>\fR
Enable HTTP Basic Authentication with the given password. Requires \fB\-\-user\fR.
Default: \fBadmin\fR if only \fB\-\-user\fR is given.

The \fBAuthorization\fR header is decoded with a hand-rolled Base64 decoder (no
external dependency). On failure, the server responds with \fB401 Unauthorized\fR
and \fBWWW-Authenticate: Basic realm="live-server"\fR.

.\" Logging
.SS "Logging"
.TP
\fB\-L\fR, \fB\-\-log-level\fR \fI<LEVEL>\fR
Log verbosity: \fBoff\fR, \fBfatal\fR, \fBerror\fR, \fBwarn\fR, \fBinfo\fR, \fBdebug\fR,
\fBtrace\fR. Default: \fBinfo\fR.
.TP
\fB\-F\fR, \fB\-\-log-file\fR \fI<FILE>\fR
Write log output to \fI<FILE>\fR instead of stderr. Colour output is
automatically disabled for file output.
.TP
\fB\-R\fR, \fB\-\-print-request\fR
Log the full raw request headers (method, path, version, all headers) at
\fBdebug\fR level for each connection. Implies \fB\-\-log-level=debug\fR.

.\" Live reload
.SS "Live Reload"
.TP
\fB\-U\fR, \fB\-\-live-reload\fR
Enable soft reload. The server injects a small \fB<script>\fR into every
\fBtext/html\fR response (single-pass \fB</body>\fR scan) that opens an
\fBEventSource\fR to \fB/livereload\fR.
.TP
\fB\-W\fR, \fB\-\-live-hard-reload\fR
Enable hard reload. Same injection mechanism, but the broadcast is
\fBdata: hard-reload\n\n\fR; the client appends \fB_lr=<timestamp>\fR to the
URL and navigates, bypassing the browser cache. Mutually exclusive with
\fB\-\-live-reload\fR.

Live reload sets \fBCache-Control: no-store\fR on injected pages to prevent
caching of the injected script.

.\" File watcher
.SS "File Watcher"
.TP
\fB\-O\fR, \fB\-\-poll\fR
Force the portable poll-based watcher (500 ms interval) instead of the native
backend. On Linux the default is \fBinotify\fR; on macOS the default is
\fBkqueue\fR. The poll watcher snapshots the entire tree and diffs mtimes
using a hash map for O(N) comparison.
.TP
\fB\-i\fR, \fB\-\-ignore\fR
Skip hidden files and directories (names starting with \fB.\fR) in the watcher.

.\" Help / Version
.SS "Information"
.TP
\fB\-\-help\fR
Display help text and exit.
.TP
\fB\-\-version\fR
Print version string and exit.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Basic usage
.B live-server
.br
Serves \fB./\fR on \fBhttp://localhost:8080\fR.
.TP
Custom directory and port
.B live-server -I ./dist -P 3000
.br
Serves \fB./dist\fR on port \fB3000\fR.
.TP
LAN access for mobile testing
.B live-server -H 0.0.0.0 -P 8080
.br
Binds to all interfaces; other devices on the same network can reach the
server at the host's LAN IP.
.TP
Soft live reload during development
.B live-server -I ./site -U
.br
Any file change triggers a soft reload in connected browsers.
.TP
Hard reload (cache-busting)
.B live-server -I ./site -W
.br
Forces full navigation with cache-busting query parameter.
.TP
Rate limit + Basic Auth
.B live-server -M 10 -u me -p secret
.br
At most 10 concurrent connections per IP; requires username \fBme\fR and
password \fBsecret\fR.
.TP
Open browser on start (macOS)
.B live-server -B open
.br
On Linux use \fB-B xdg-open\fR or \fB-B firefox\fR.

.SH FILE WATCHER BACKENDS
The watcher runs in a dedicated pthread and calls the callback on change.
.TP
Linux (default)
\fBinotify\fR (recursive). Creates a watch descriptor for the root and every
subdirectory. New directories are auto-watched on \fBIN_CREATE|\fR\fBIN_MOVED_TO\fR.
Uses \fBselect(2)\fR on the inotify fd + a wake pipe for shutdown.
.TP
macOS (default)
\fBkqueue\fR (recursive). Opens each directory with \fBO_EVTONLY\fR and registers
\fBEVFILT_VNODE\fR with \fBNOTE_WRITE|NOTE_EXTEND|NOTE_ATTRIB|NOTE_LINK|
NOTE_RENAME|NOTE_REVOKE|NOTE_DELETE\fR. New directories are scanned and added
on \fBNOTE_WRITE|NOTE_LINK|NOTE_RENAME\fR. Uses \fBkevent(2)\fR with a 2-second
timeout + wake pipe.
.TP
Fallback (Linux \fB\-\-poll\fR or if native backend fails)
Periodic snapshot every 500 ms. Builds an in-memory array of (path, mtime)
pairs and compares against the previous snapshot using a 4096-slot hash map
with full-path keys (truncated to 63 chars) for O(N) diff. Uses \fBselect(2)\fR
on a wake pipe.

.SH ACCESS LOG FORMAT
Each request produces one line on stderr:
.nf
[HH:MM:SS.mmmmmm] [LEVEL] CLIENT_IP:CLIENT_PORT "METHOD PATH VERSION" STATUS - (BYTES bytes, MIME)
.fi
Example:
.nf
[12:34:56.789012] [INFO ] 127.0.0.1:54321 "GET /index.html HTTP/1.1" 200 - (3012 bytes, text/html)
.fi
With \fB\-\-print-request\fR, the raw headers follow at debug level.

.SH PERFORMANCE CHARACTERISTICS
.TP
Linux static files
\fBsendfile()\fR zero-copy kernel\u2192socket for non-range GET requests.
.TP
Headers
Date/Server/Connection pre-formatted once per second; \fBwritev()\fR emits
headers + body in one syscall.
.TP
Thread-local buffers
Per-thread grow-only body buffers eliminate \fBmalloc/free\fR on the read path.
.TP
Lock-free logging
Producer: atomic \fBfetch_add\fR + format into ring slot (~50 ns).
Consumer: batched \fBfwrite\fR + single \fBfflush\fR.
.TP
Rate limiter
Dynamic hash table, grows 2\u00d7 at 75% load; IP strings freed at count=0.
.TP
SSE registry
1024-bucket hash map; O(1) add/remove/broadcast.

.SH SIGNALS
.TP
\fBSIGINT\fR, \fBSIGTERM\fR
Graceful shutdown: stops accept loop, drains thread pool (workers finish
current task), stops watcher, closes listener, joins all threads.
.TP
\fBSIGPIPE\fR
Ignored (\fBSIG_IGN\fR). Write errors on closed sockets are handled via
return values.

.SH FILES
No configuration files, no environment variables, no runtime state outside
the process. All settings via command line.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\fB0\fR
Successful shutdown (signal received).
.TP
\fB1\fR
Startup failure: bind error, thread pool creation failure, watcher creation
failure, invalid arguments.

.SH LIMITATIONS
.TP
\fBNo HTTPS/TLS\fR
Pair with a reverse proxy (nginx, Caddy, mkcert) for local HTTPS.
.TP
\fBNo compression\fR
\fBgzip\fR/\fBbrotli\fR omitted — dev tools show uncompressed sizes; compression
would complicate live-reload injection.
.TP
\fBNo directory listing\fR
If a directory lacks \fBindex.html\fR, returns \fB404\fR (not \fB403\fR).
.TP
\fBNo HTTP/2\fR
Single-threaded accept + thread pool is HTTP/1.1 only.
.TP
\fBWhole file in memory for injection\fR
HTML files are read completely for \fB</body>\fR scan + script injection.
Not suitable for multi-GB files.

